Japan, Malaysia South Korea, Taiwan: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 
2011-06-12T23:04:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-12/japan-malaysia-south-korea-taiwan-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The  Bank of Japan  ends a two-day policy board meeting
today. The central bank is forecast to keep the benchmark
interest at zero to 0.1 percent, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The Cabinet Office is set to report the nation’s machine
orders for April at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo. Orders, an indicator of
business investment in three to six months, rose 1.7 percent
following a 1 percent increase in April, according to the median
estimate of economists in a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 1.2 percent government bond due June 2021
was 1.130 percent on June 10, according to Japan Bond Trading
Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  South Korea : The government will sell 1.6 trillion won
($1.5 billion) of five-year bonds today.  The yield on the 5 percent bond due June 2020 was 4.25
percent. The won was at 1,082.65 per dollar.  Taiwan: The government will buy back NT$75 billion ($2.6
billion) of treasury bills today.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.53
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The  Taiwan
dollar  was at NT$28.835.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell 2 billion ringgit
($662 million) of 131-day notes, 1 billion ringgit of 163-day
notes and 500 million ringgit of 182-day Islamic notes today.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 3.93 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0210.  Philippines : The government will sell 1.5 billion pesos
($35 million) of 91-day bills and 3.5 billion pesos of 182-day
bills today. It will also sell 4 billion pesos of 364-day bills.  The yield on the 9.125 percent bond due September 2016 was
5.33 percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The
peso was at 43.245 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
